He has echoed President Cyril Ramaphosa’s assurance to South Africans that government will closely monitor the use of the funds. This follows widespread concerns that the money will be siphoned as happened to the Covid-19 relief funds. Gungubele was part of a virtual media briefing. “What the President said is that structures like labour, community based organisations, business and religious leaders and the private sector are expected to be a part of the broader oversight movement.” Meanwhile, South Africa's major port of Durban, where operations were disrupted by severe flooding last week, is now functional and a backlog of thousands of containers will be cleared within five to six days, the Public Enterprises Minister said on Tuesday. The floods caused extensive damage to roads leading to Durban port, one of the busiest shipping terminals in Africa and a key hub for exports like metals and agricultural commodities and imports like fuel. --SABC--